      <h1>Apiary layout basics</h1>
      <p class="lede">Positioning hives for safety, efficiency, and healthy bee flight lines in any setting.</p>

      <div class="grid cols-3">
        <section class="card" id="site-choice">
          <h2>Choosing a site</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li><strong>Sunlight:</strong> morning sun warms the entrance early; partial afternoon shade prevents overheating.</li>
            <li><strong>Shelter:</strong> hedge, fence, or trees to break cold winds but not block airflow.</li>
            <li><strong>Access:</strong> flat ground, year-round entry for lifting boxes safely.</li>
            <li><strong>Water:</strong> clean nearby source prevents bees crowding neighboursâ€™ ponds.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card" id="orientation">
          <h2>Hive orientation</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li>Entrances ideally face <strong>south-east</strong> for early warmth.</li>
            <li>Vary facing angles slightly between hives to reduce drifting.</li>
            <li>Keep clear <strong>flight paths</strong> (2â€“3 m in front) free of tall obstacles.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card" id="spacing">
          <h2>Spacing & layout</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li><strong>Between hives:</strong> ~1 m minimum, 2â€“3 m ideal.</li>
            <li><strong>Rows:</strong> stagger so entrances donâ€™t align directly opposite each other.</li>
            <li>Label or colour-code boxes to help bees orient by visual cues.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>
      </div>

      <div class="divider"></div>

      <section id="urban">
        <h2>Urban and garden settings</h2>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Keep entrances above head height or behind screens to lift flight lines.</li>
          <li>Maintain considerate distances from paths, neighbours, and boundaries.</li>
          <li>Provide shallow water source (pebbles in trays) during dry spells.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="notice">Check local council or landlord permissions before placing hives on rooftops or allotments.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="rural">
        <h2>Rural and out-apiary setups</h2>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Ensure solid stands: paving slabs, bricks, or treated timber blocks.</li>
          <li>Protect from livestock with fencing or rails.</li>
          <li>Watch for damp hollowsâ€”hives need dry feet.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section id="workflow">
        <h2>Workflow & safety</h2>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Leave at least one clear side for inspections (ideally the back).</li>
          <li>Keep smoker, tools, and spare supers on a portable stand within easy reach.</li>
          <li>Mark an emergency retreat path free of clutter or trip hazards.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

